France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lacy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lassy in Calvados, named from a Gaulish personal name <i>Lascius</i> (of uncertain origin and meaning) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lasee","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English or Irish   Lacy  ."]},{"name":"Lacey","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Lacy  ."]}]},{"name":"Ilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":21,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":41,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ilbert de Lacy 1st Baron of Pontefract was born in 1045, in Normandy, France. He died in 1093, in Pontefract, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 48, and was buried in Pontefract, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1045–1093":"1045–1093","1040–1109":"1040–1109","1045–1135":"1045–1135","1064–Female":"1064–Surnud","1065–Male":"1065–Surnud","1070–1129":"1070–1129","1073–Female":"1073–Surnud","about 1093":"umbes 1093","about 1073":"umbes 1073","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1064":"1064","1086":"1086","1073":"1073","1040":"1040","1093":"1093","1070":"1070","1129":"1129","1135":"1135","1045":"1045","about 1065":"umbes 1065","20 May 1070":"20. mai 1070","1109":"1109","Loei, Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Yorkshire West Riding, England,":"Yorkshire West Riding, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Halton, Cheshire, England":"Halton, Cheshire, England","Pontefract, Yorkshire, England":"Pontefract, Yorkshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1045–1093":"1045–1093","1040–1109":"1040–1109","1045–1135":"1045–1135","1064–Female":"1064–Kuollut","1065–Mal